    9501        1548 : void set_template_decl_lookup_sequence(a_scope_depth initial_depth)
    9502             : /*

    9509             : table illustrates how the scope stack is updated as each scope is
    9510             : pushed for this example:

    9512             :   namespace A { namespace B { template <class T> void f(); } }
    9513             :   template <class T> void A::B::f(){}

    9516             : the scope kind, and P is the previous scope for name lookup purposes.
    9517             : 
    9518             :   Initial                 After namespace A      After namespace B
    9519             :   state                   is reactivated         is reactivated
    9520             :   -----------------       -----------------      -----------------
    9521             :                                                  3 ns react B (2)
    9522             :                           2 ns react A (0)       2 ns react A (0)
    9523             :   1 templ. decl. (0)      1 templ. decl. (2)     1 templ. decl. (3)
    9524             :   0 file (none)           0 file (none)          0 file (none)
    9525             :

    9527             :

    9529             : pushed for a Microsoft template specialization scope.  This is done

    9531             : inside of the instantiation scope pushed for the specialization.

   11603     3918270 : a_boolean begin_potential_pack_expansion_context_full(

   11608             : /*
   11609             : This is called at the start of a construct that could be a variadic template
   11610             : pack expansion.  Such pack expansions occur only within the declarations
   11611             : and bodies of templates.  This routine is called when entering a potential
   11612             : pack expansion context.  In most cases it will turn out that the context
   11613             : does not actually contain a pack expansion.  In the example below, this
   11614             : routine is called at the points marked with "^".   On each of the lines, the
   11615             : first "^" is not actually a pack expansion but the second one is.
   11616             : 
   11617             :   template <class ... T> void f(int i, T ... args){
   11618             :                                 ^      ^
   11619             :     h(1, (args+1)...);

   11624             : instantiation can be done.  During the prototype instantiation the token
   11625             : range of each actual pack expansion is recorded.  A list of the parameter packs
   11626             : actually referenced from within the expansion is also recorded.  When we
   11627             : reach the corresponding potential pack expansion context during a real
   11628             : instantiation we know which argument values, if any, need to be expanded.
   11629             : 
   11630             : This routine returns TRUE if there are any argument values to be expanded or
   11631             : if this is not an actual pack expansion.  In other words, it returns FALSE
   11632             : for an actual pack expansion for which the associated parameter packs have
   11633             : zero elements.  It will also issue an error and return FALSE for a pack
   11634             : expansion that uses multiple parameter packs but for which the parameter
   11635             : packs do not all have the same number of elements.  When FALSE is returned,
   11636             : the token stream will be advanced so that the current token is the one
